# Git Workflow

- Do not create commits, tags, branches, or pull requests unless explicitly requested.
- Before any commit or PR, inspect `git status`, relevant `git diff`, and recent commit messages.
- Never use destructive commands such as `git reset --hard`, `git checkout --`, `git clean -fd`, or force-push unless the user explicitly asks.
- Do not amend commits unless the user explicitly requests it.
- Never rewrite shared history on `main` or `master`.
- Keep unrelated local changes intact; work around them instead of reverting them.
- When making a commit, stage only files related to the requested task.
- If a hook fails, fix the problem and create a new commit instead of bypassing hooks.
- Do not change git config in this repository.
- If the workspace is not a git repository, do not invent git operations; explain the limitation and continue with file work.
